         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">28/8/80 ¶  ¶ The little book of Rev. G. Henslow, your brother in law, ¶  is very pleasing, dear Sir Joseph, and nothing better could be offered to the rising youth for imbibing the first knowledge on ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">80.08.28</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, f. 287.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS annotation by Hooker: 'And [Nvr] 8/80'.</p>
               </note>28/8/80</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The little book of Rev. G. Henslow, your brother in law,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Henslow (1880).</p>
               </note> is very pleasing, dear Sir Joseph, and nothing better could be offered to the rising youth for imbibing the first knowledge on plants. I endeavoured to strike out some similar path in my "Teachings",<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B77.08.01. See Lucas, Maroske &amp; Brown-May (2006).</p>
               </note> though not acquainted then with the Rev Gentleman's efforts in the same direction.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>By last mail I sent you the number of the fragmenta, which contains my latest notes on Palms.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to J. Hooker, 10 August 1880. B80.02.02 contains notes on palms at pp. 88-9.</p>
               </note> I also sent a few pieces of Palm specimens, so far as I had them, to your request.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See J. Hooker to M, 10 June 1880, and J. Hooker to M, 5 July 1880.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Travelling in <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">our</hi>
               </seg> palm regions is so expensive and difficult and often very dangerous, that it is not surprising when we find the material so unsatisfactory.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Still, some of the collectors, particularly Dallachy, whom I have paid at the rate of £150 for 10 years as collector, might have done much better. The excuse was often, that it was such a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">thirsty</hi>
               </seg> country to travel through, before one get to the brooks, on which Palms grow.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">After</hi>
               </seg> the Exhibition<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">International exhibition, Melbourne, 1880-1.</p>
               </note> I may take a ramble to the north myself, though it will be [very]<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Uncertain transcription: word partly obscured by binding</seg>.</p>
               </note> expensive, to move about in the pristine pathless forests or fever-jungles.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M did not make the trip.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I anticipated you in the transfer of <name key="Kentia%20minor">Kentia minor</name> to <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Bacularia">Bacularia</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>,<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M described <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Kentia%20minor">Kentia minor</name>
                     </seg> in B74.09.02, p. 235, but referred it to <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Bacularia">Bacularia</name> minor</seg> in B78.11.04, p. 58.</p>
               </note> which genus was sufficiently defined for Wendland's ad[o]ptation, who rather selfishly put forward his <name key="Linospadix">Linospadix</name>, and who can well afford to leave in fairness at least that one genus to me.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M erected <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Bacularia">Bacularia</name>
                     </seg>(<seg style="font-style: italic; ">B. monostachya</seg>) in B78.11.04, p. 58. M had provisionally given the name <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Bacularia">Bacularia</name>
                     </seg> in B70.04.01, p. 103, and he is commenting on the footnote to H. Wendland &amp; Drude (1875), p. 198, where it is claimed that the characters of the genus <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Linospadix">Linospadix</name>
                     </seg> had been recorded, but not printed, in 1861 when it was introduced into the gardens in Hanover.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">You will be aware, that I reduced <name key="Kentiopsis">Kentiopsis</name> (<seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">before Beccari</hi>
               </seg>) to Kentia in the fragm.<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M described a number of species of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Kentia</seg> in B70.04.01, pp. 99-104.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Drude abopts<note xml:id="ftn12" type="footnote" n="12">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">adopts? No published evidence that Drude recognized the genus at this time has been found, but he treated it as a subgenus of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Linospadix">Linospadix</name>
                     </seg> in Drude (1889), p. 67.</p>
               </note> now <name key="Bacularia">Bacularia</name> also.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>
               <name key="Bacularia">Bacularia</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Kentia%20minor">Kentia minor</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Kentiopsis">Kentiopsis</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Linospadix">Linospadix</name>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
         </div>
